  "doc_id": "38586",
  "text": "Interface specifications in languages such as Eiffel [CITATION_1] , the Java Modeling Language (JML) [CITATION_2] , and Spec# [CITATION_3] use expressions of the programming language in pre-and postconditions, object invariants, and other assertions. In particular, specifications are allowed to contain method calls, which are useful for two major purposes. First, methods are a means of abstraction. They allow one to express properties of a data structure without exposing its implementation details. Second, methods are a unit of reuse. Using methods in specifications avoids the duplication of specifications. For instance, using a square root method in specifications avoids repeating the properties of square root wherever they are needed.",
